    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='## Analysis: Determinable vs. Amendment-Required Disclosures in SpaceX\'s Preliminary S-1\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) is a preliminary prospectus that explicitly states "The information in this preliminary prospectus is not complete and may be changed." The cover page, beneficial ownership tables, and certain risk-factor disclosures contain blank placeholders ("$________", "________ shares", "________%") for offering-price, share-count, and post-IPO percentage figures. Below is the item-by-item determination.\n\n---\n\n### (i) Post-IPO Fully Diluted Share Count — **REQUIRES AMENDMENT DISCLOSURE**\n\n**Cannot be determined from the filing as filed.**\n\n- The cover page table leaves both post-offering share counts blank:\n  - "Class A common stock outstanding immediately after this offering … ________ shares (or ________ shares if the underwriters exercise their option to purchase additional shares…)."\n  - "Class B common stock outstanding immediately after this offering … ________ shares."\n- The number of Class A shares offered, the over-allotment option size, and any concurrent private placements are all blank.\n- The fee table registers **66,666,670 shares** with proposed maximum aggregate offering prices escalating from $5.5 trillion to $7.5 trillion — but these are bona fide estimates used solely for calculating the SEC registration fee, not the actual offering size. They do not yield a determinable post-IPO share count.\n- **What IS disclosed (pre-offering only):** 6,932,508,000 Class A shares and 5,602,790,410 Class B shares outstanding as of May 1, 2026. This establishes the pre-IPO base but not the post-IPO fully diluted count, which depends on the (undisclosed) offering size, greenshoe exercise, and any RSU/option settlement at closing.\n\n**Conclusion:** The post-IPO fully diluted share count is not determinable and must be supplied via amendment (typically the cover page and capitalization table in a subsequent S-1/A).\n\n---\n\n### (ii) Class A versus Class B Economic Ownership — **REQUIRES AMENDMENT DISCLOSURE (post-IPO)**\n\n**Cannot be determined for the post-IPO period; pre-IPO split is calculable.**\n\n- **Structural/economic equivalence IS disclosed:** Class A and Class B are economically identical — holders receive dividends "pro rata, on an equal priority, pari passu basis" and share ratably in liquidation. The only differences are voting (1 vote vs. 10 votes) and conversion (Class B → Class A on transfer). Therefore, economic ownership is driven entirely by share count, not by class-specific economic preferences.\n- **Pre-IPO economic split is calculable from disclosed share counts:**\n  - Class A: 6,932,508,000 / 12,535,298,410 = **55.30%** economic ownership\n  - Class B: 5,602,790,410 / 12,535,298,410 = **44.70%** economic ownership\n- **Post-IPO economic ownership is NOT determinable:** The beneficial ownership table\'s "Shares Beneficially Owned After This Offering" columns are blank, and the post-offering share counts (item (i) above) are blank. The filing states the post-offering percentages are "based on [blank] shares of our Class A common stock and [blank] shares of our Class B common stock outstanding… after giving effect to the sale of [blank] shares of Class A common stock in this offering."\n\n**Conclusion:** The economic equivalence of the two classes is disclosed, and the pre-IPO economic split is calculable. However, the post-IPO Class A vs. Class B economic ownership split requires amendment disclosure because it depends on the undisclosed offering size.\n\n---\n\n### (iii) Musk\'s Post-IPO Voting Control — **PARTIALLY DETERMINABLE (qualitative yes; exact percentage requires amendment)**\n\n**The qualitative fact of majority voting control IS determinable; the exact percentage is NOT.**\n\n- **Definitive qualitative disclosure (determinable as filed):** The S-1 states unambiguously: *"Upon completion of this offering, Mr. Musk will beneficially own a majority of the outstanding shares of our Class B common stock and a majority of the voting power of the common stock (the Class A common stock and the Class B common stock voting together) and therefore will be able to elect all the members of our board."*\n- **Structural mechanisms supporting this conclusion are disclosed:**\n  - Class B carries 10 votes/share vs. Class A\'s 1 vote/share.\n  - Class B holders, voting separately as a class, elect 51% of authorized directors.\n  - Musk can only be removed from his board/leadership roles by a majority vote of outstanding Class B shares.\n  - The company will be a "controlled company" under Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas rules.\n- **Pre-IPO voting power IS disclosed:** Musk holds 849,494,440 Class A shares (12.3% of Class A) and 5,569,053,075 Class B shares (93.6% of Class B, including 350,000,000 Class B shares issuable upon option exercise within 60 days), combining for **85.1% of pre-offering voting power**.\n- **Post-IPO exact percentage is NOT determinable:** The filing states: *"Elon Musk… will hold approximately [blank] % of the voting power of our common stock (or approximately [blank] % if the underwriters exercise their option to purchase additional shares of Class A common stock in full) immediately after the completion of this offering…"*\n\n**Conclusion:** The filing as filed definitively establishes that Musk will retain majority post-IPO voting control (a qualitative, structural conclusion). The precise post-IPO voting percentage requires amendment disclosure because it depends on the undisclosed offering size and share count.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Item | Determinable as Filed? | Amendment Required? |\n|------|----------------------|---------------------|\n| (i) Post-IPO fully diluted share count | **No** — cover page and capitalization blanks; fee-table share count is a fee estimate only | **Yes** |\n| (ii) Class A vs. Class B economic ownership (post-IPO) | **No** — post-offering beneficial ownership columns blank; pre-IPO split (55.30% A / 44.70% B) is calculable but post-IPO is not | **Yes** (for post-IPO figures) |\n| (iii) Musk\'s post-IPO voting control | **Partially** — qualitative majority control is definitively stated; pre-IPO 85.1% disclosed; exact post-IPO % is blank | **Yes** (for exact post-IPO percentage only) |\n\nThe key analytical distinction: the S-1\'s dual-class architecture and Musk\'s pre-IPO holdings (93.6% of Class B, 85.1% voting power) are sufficient to conclude as a matter of disclosed fact that he will retain majority voting control post-IPO. But any precise post-IPO figure — share count, economic ownership split, or voting percentage — depends on the offering size, which the preliminary prospectus deliberately omits and which must be supplied in an amendment.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (SpaceX) Form S-1 Registration Statement, filed May 20, 2026"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
